        	T H E    G A M E    P L A Y E R ' S    D O C S

			     March 7, 1992

	Welcome to The Game Player's Docs series of game documenation disks.
As an Amiga game collector since 1985 and former arcade game programmer,
I've found it quite difficult to play many Amiga games without documentation.
While many games seem simple to play, you don't always know what the object
of the game is, and often there are hidden features within the game. Besides
many newer Amiga games are becoming more complex, and you will never figure
them out without documentation. Also, with these docs you may discover
many older games that you overlooked, especially among newer Amiga owners
who just see certain titles advertised in the magazines or those sold in the
computer stores. There are hundreds of classic games just two or three years
old, but worth playing. Look for used copies for sale at your local user
group. People tire of games and often sell them for under ten dollars.
	I've been collecting docs disks seriously within the last two years.
The files on many of these disks are in random order, often duplicates or
obviously taken off BBSs or services like PeopleLink or Compuserve with junk
embedded within them. I attempted to sort and clean up the worst of the mess.

